LearningStatement.510: In business, cover is a buyer's right to substitute goods for those due under a sales or lease agreement when the seller provides nonconforming goods.
LearningStatement.511: In business, enough refers to the point at which increased spending has a diminishing rate of fulfillment.
LearningStatement.512: In business, exploitation refers to applying current knowledge to enhance firm performance in the short term.
LearningStatement.513: In business, erosion is the cash flow amount transferred to a new project from customers and sales of other products of the firm.
LearningStatement.514: In business, events are happenings that both affect an organization's financial position and can be reliably measured.
LearningStatement.515: In business, exploration is searching for new knowledge that may enhance future performance.
LearningStatement.516: In business, myopia refers the to the difficulty human beings have with conceptualizing the more distant future, leading to decisions that overly favor present and near-term options at the expense of more distant future possibilities.
LearningStatement.517: In business, inadequacy refers to the condition in which the capacity of plant assets is too small to meet the company's production demands.
LearningStatement.518: In business, oppression is the officers, directors, or controlling shareholder's isolation of one group of shareholders for disadvantageous treatment to the benefit of another group of shareholders.
LearningStatement.519: In business, people are part of the organizational architecture that includes strategy used to recruit, compensate, and retain employees.

LearningStatement.530: In business, choking is a slang term used to describe the observed performance decrements under pressure circumstances.

LearningStatement.569: In economics, an aggregate is a collection of specific economic units treated as if they were one unit.
